WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
My name is Tareef Kawaf, I'm president of RStudio, and I do this probably once a year at useR!

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:11.000
just to give people a chance to give people an update on what we've been up to, and then, frankly,

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:15.000
hopefully get some questions and have some dialogue. There's a lot to cover, so I'm going to try

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:19.000
and run through things pretty quickly. This particular conference was interesting because

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:23.000
I ended up with a whole bunch of conversations that highlighted that maybe we need to spend a little more time

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:29.000
talking about who we are and what we do, which is not something that I

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:33.000
was planning on, but anyway, so this is our mission. It's pretty straightforward.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:37.000
It's aspirational, obviously, and as you can see by the name of the company,

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:41.000
we're very much dedicated to R. We think that R is a fantastic ecosystem,

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:45.000
and we want to make sure that that continues to be a free and open source solution

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:49.000
that's available to people regardless of their economic means.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:55.000
So when you look at how we think about the world, we believe that all the work that you do

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:01.000
should be reproducible, and that invariably ends up meaning that we believe that it should be in code,

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:08.000
and so... Sorry?

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:13.000
Okay. It's not me, right? All right.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:18.000
I'm like, I can't do anything else. All right. So we believe in APIs, designing good APIs,

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.000
trying to figure out what are the ways that make it really easy for the data scientists

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.000
to get their work done. Excellent.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:30.000
I know that's not for me either. I know. I got it. I got it.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:35.000
All right. So 70% of the engineering that we do goes into open source software,

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:39.000
and I'll walk you guys through some of the things that we've done, and then...

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:43.000
And our plan for... Actually, JJ and I met about four and a half years ago,

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:46.000
and our plan from day one was to say, okay, in order for this to really work,

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:51.000
we need to have a structure, a company that is able to generate enough revenue

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:54.000
so that we can hire the top minds so that they can, you know, top engineers

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:56.000
that can actually work on solving these problems, right?

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:01.000
And so the company itself structurally is designed to make that happen,

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:05.000
and so what we decided to do is we built these commercial products.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:09.000
We take our server products, and we add features and capabilities around them

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:12.000
that really are about enterprise fit.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:15.000
So, like, larger organizations that are already spending a lot of money on IT

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:19.000
can go and say, okay, great, if I'm counting on R and I'm counting on Shiny

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:23.000
or I'm counting on RStudio, I have a way to be able to sort of call somebody,

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:27.000
but more importantly maybe is make sure that everything plugs into

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.000
what I would expect it to plug into within my existing infrastructure.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:33.000
So we put a lot of features around security, authentication, monitoring,

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:37.000
tuning, scaling, metrics, high availability, low balancing, et cetera,

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:38.000
these kinds of things.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:41.000
So those of you in the audience who are our customers, thank you very much.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:44.000
The rest of the slides and a lot of the slides I'm going to show you here

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:47.000
are only possible because you guys are buying our commercial products.

