00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:31.000
and then the organization says, hey, you broke it when you did X or Y or Z.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:38.000
We recognize that because the background of our community is data scientists, right?

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:40.000
They're not software engineers by training.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:42.000
And the tooling is not that great.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:45.000
We're trying to create tooling that makes life easier for folks.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:50.000
And my colleague Barbara talked about pools, so I won't cover that too much.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:52.000
R Markdown, there's a new format called Bookdown.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:54.000
How many people have heard of Bookdown?

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:58.000
Okay, so Bookdown is a format that makes it easy for you to write books in it.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:04.000
We'll show you the website that you guys can go to and take a look at it and play with it.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:07.000
And how many people are familiar with parameterized reports?

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:09.000
Okay.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:11.000
Okay, that's what I expected.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:14.000
So parameterized reports are, you know, you guys are familiar with R Markdown docs.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:16.000
You can write R Markdown docs.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:19.000
You can actually pass in parameters.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:21.000
If you write your R Markdown doc in a certain way,

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:24.000
you can have something in the YAML file that specifies what the parameters are.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:27.000
And then you could render the doc by passing it in the arguments

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:29.000
and use those arguments within the report.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:32.000
That allows you to sort of essentially personalize a report if you want to

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:35.000
or reuse the core logic for, you know, something like,

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:38.000
okay, I might run the same report but for this different date range

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:41.000
or run the same report but for North America versus South America, whatever, right?

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:46.000
All right, we published a new book, R for Data Science.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:48.000
And when I say we, I don't mean me.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:50.000
I mean Garrett and Hadley.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:53.000
And you can, if you don't have, are you guys familiar with it?

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:54.000
Yes?

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:55.000
Kind of, sort of?

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:57.000
