And so if you guys are available at the end of January, early February,

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:31.000
you're obviously more than welcome to come along.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:34.000
All right, so how we think about data science.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:36.000
You guys may have seen this before.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:37.000
Oops.

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:39.000
All right, that's good.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:41.000
You know, you import data, you tidy the data, you transform the data,

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:43.000
you visualize the data, you model the data, and you keep going.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:47.000
And then eventually the key thing behind doing all data analysis is to communicate, right?

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:48.000
And so...

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:57.000
All right, so we decided to build a product

00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:59.000
based on feedback that we got from customers.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:01.000
And just to be clear, this product is a professional product.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:03.000
And right now it's only available on premise,

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:08.000
but ultimately in time we imagine that we will have a cloud-based solution

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:11.000
that everybody in the community can sort of leverage if they want to, right?

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:16.000
And what this product is aimed at is making it really easy

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:19.000
to go from an analysis to being able to sort of share that with the rest of the world.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:23.000
So it's push, button, deploy of all the artifacts that you sort of create out of R.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:26.000
It's an on-premise solution because most of our company customers

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:29.000
will not run any of their stuff outside of their firewalls.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:32.000
And so, again, if you want to think about it,

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:35.000
you've got, you know, you guys are the creators of analyses.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:39.000
You may create notebooks, you have static docs, you have presentations,

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:41.000
you may have parameterized R Markdown docs, as I said earlier,

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:43.000
you can have shiny applications.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:46.000
And ultimately your goal is to communicate this to somebody, right?

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:48.000
Somebody in the organization needs to be able to see this,

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:51.000
and so we're trying to also build in things like, you know, scheduling.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:55.000
So if you wanted a report to run every Monday and email people out or whatever,

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:59.000
you can sort of do things like that without having to sort of write your own crontabs

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:02.000
or, you know, have a separate system call into it.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:04.000
Now if you want to, you can absolutely do the same thing.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:07.000
The foundation of everything that you see here is all open source, right?

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:11.000
People can recreate this themselves at any point in time, and I expect that they will.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:16.000
In terms of, so again, the creators, there's artifacts, there's consumers,

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:19.000
and you guys are all familiar with the work of the creator, right?

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:22.000
So you're tidying that whole tidy, transform, visualize model,

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:26.000
but you also care about reproducibility, you care about collaboration,

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.000
you care about publishing, you care about protecting, right?

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:31.000
So who can see this content, when can they see it, and so on and so forth, right?

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:35.000
And then on the consumer side, they want to be able to get a hold of the data,

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:38.000
they want to be able to explore the data, they may want to personalize it,

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:41.000
say, I'm only interested in reports about North America,

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:44.000
or I'm only interested in Southern Italy, right?

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:50.000
Or they may want to say, I know I saw, you know, Joe showed me a report or a dashboard,

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:53.000
I want to see what that looks like today, can I go back and rerun that myself, right?

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:56.000
So the idea is if you've already built this logic in R,

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:00.000
we're going to try and make it more and more accessible to the business user.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:02.000
All right, so that's what Connect does.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:09.000
And, you know, a lot of our work ends up being providing features

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:13.000
to answer questions for the IT organization on why R, right?

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:17.000
The data scientists are bought in, they use it, they're building really great things,

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:20.000
and then they run into these obstacles within the IT organization.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:23.000
So, you know, we spend a lot of time trying to say, okay, you know what,

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:26.000
here's how you tune this, here's how you monitor this, here's how you scale it.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:33.000
For Connect, for example, I just spent a pile of cash on an external security vendor firm

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:37.000
to come in and validate and make sure that, hey, you know what,

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:41.000
here are the issues that we found, that there's an independent person taking a look at that.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:46.000
And so we have a higher bar to cross over because, you know, for IT,

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:49.000
they're very familiar with a Python solution, a Python stack,

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:53.000
and in many ways they ask the data scientists on the R side

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:56.000
to hold themselves to a higher standard than what, you know,

00:10:56.000 --> 00:11:00.000
what even the rest of the organization is held to.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:04.000
But our job is to hopefully make it easier and easier for that sell to happen.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:07.000
So deployment is a push-button deployment.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:11.000
We identify dependencies, you know, we use Packer right underneath the hood.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:14.000
We match up our versions to the best of our abilities,

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:19.000
and so the idea is get more of these artifacts to be published quickly.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:23.000
The reports, all the reporting is based on our markdown,

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:25.000
so it's completely reproducible.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:27.000
You can schedule it, you can email it, you know, ultimately in time,

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:30.000
you can imagine that you can also have that drop into a location on disk

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:32.000
or drop into Confluence,

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:39.000
or potentially, like, send a Slack message or whatever, right?

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:42.000
And you can customize, you can give the end user the opportunity

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.000
to sort of customize the report that they see

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:46.000
based on the parameters that they're interested in.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:50.000
And obviously, it can do everything around hosting Shiny applications.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:53.000
So generally, architecturally, this is what it looks like.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:57.000
You know, you've got the data scientist publishing on one side,

00:11:57.000 --> 00:11:59.000
you've got the end user sort of interacting with it as a web browser.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:02.000
They don't know that they're talking to anything that is R-related.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:07.000
So useful websites, shiny.rstudio.com,

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:10.000
I'm guessing everybody here knows about it.

